  "text": "In the kubernetes/kubernetes repository, controllers register themselves with the controller-manager (Manager) through a structured registration system. The key pattern involves several components:\n\n1. **ControllerDescriptor Registration** (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:495-522):\n   Controllers are registered via `ControllerDescriptor` structs that contain a Name() and InitFunc(). The NewControllerDescriptors() function creates a map of all known controllers and their descriptors using a register() function. Each descriptor includes the controller's initialization function.\n\n2. **InitFunc Pattern** (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:419):\n   Each controller is defined by an `InitFunc` which is called to create and start the controller. The signature is:\n   `type InitFunc func(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, controllerName string) (controller controller.Interface, enabled bool, err error)`\n\n3. **Controller Interface** (staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go:26-29):\n   Controllers must implement the `Interface` interface which requires a Name() method. Additional optional interfaces include Debuggable and HealthCheckable for debugging and health checks.\n\n4. **StartController Entry Point** (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/controllermanager.go:710-761):\n   The StartController() function orchestrates controller startup. It:\n   - Validates feature gates\n   - Calls the controller's InitFunc to create the controller\n   - Registers debugging handlers if the controller implements Debuggable\n   - Registers health checks if the controller implements HealthCheckable\n\n5. **Example: Deployment Controller Registration** (cmd/kube-controller-manager/app/apps.go:98-105):\n   Controllers are registered with descriptors like:\n   ```go\n   func newDeploymentControllerDescriptor() *ControllerDescriptor {\n       return &ControllerDescriptor{\n           name:     names.DeploymentController,\n           aliases:  []string{\"deployment\"},\n           initFunc: startDeploymentController,\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n6. **Initialization and Reconciliation Loop** (pkg/controller/deployment/deployment_controller.go:100-185):\n   The startDeploymentController InitFunc creates a DeploymentController and calls its Run() method. The controller:\n   - Sets up event handlers on informers (AddEventHandler) to watch Deployment, ReplicaSet, and Pod resources\n   - Uses a work queue to queue items that need reconciliation\n   - Spawns multiple worker goroutines that process items from the queue\n   - Each worker calls syncDeployment (the syncHandler) to perform the actual reconciliation\n\n7. **Worker and Sync Pattern** (pkg/controller/deployment/deployment_controller.go:482-625):\n   The worker() goroutine runs a reconciliation loop that:\n   - Dequeues items from the work queue\n   - Calls syncDeployment() to reconcile the deployment's desired state with the actual state\n   - Handles retries and backoff using rate limiting\n\nThis pattern is the kubernetes equivalent of the controller-runtime's SetupWithManager approach. While controller-runtime uses a Reconciler interface with SetupWithManager() to register controllers, kubernetes controllers use ControllerDescriptor with InitFunc to register themselves with the manager. Both patterns achieve the same goal: registering controllers to watch resources, populate work queues, and execute reconciliation loops through worker goroutines."
}

